1. Core Characteristics
- JavaScript arrays are resizable Array objects (not primitives) that can contain mixed data types. Arrays are zero-indexed; first element at index 0; last element index = length - 1.

2. Indices and length relationship
- Valid array indices are non-negative integers (or their string equivalents). Setting arr[5] updates length to at least 6. Increasing length via arr.length = N creates empty slots without element entries; decreasing length truncates and deletes elements beyond new length.

3. Empty slots and method semantics
- Sparse arrays contain empty slots. Iteration methods differ in treating empty slots: forEach, map, filter skip empty slots; newer methods like keys, entries, values treat empty slots as undefined. Methods like concat/copyWithin preserve empty slots.

4. Mutating vs non-mutating methods
- Mutating methods: copyWithin, fill, pop, push, reverse, shift, sort, splice, unshift. Non-mutating alternatives: use slice, concat, toReversed, toSorted, toSpliced, or use spread operator to copy first.
- Where possible prefer non-mutating alternatives to maintain immutability in functional code.

5. Iterative callback signatures
- Methods that accept callbacks use signature callback(element, index, array) and optional thisArg. ForEach and other iterative methods call callback at most once per present element in index order.

Supplementary Details

Technical specifications and implementation details
- Common method signatures and returns:
  - push(...items) -> number (new length)
  - pop() -> any (removed element or undefined)
  - shift() -> any
  - unshift(...items) -> number (new length)
  - slice(start?, end?) -> Array
  - splice(start, deleteCount?, ...items) -> Array (removed elements)
  - map(callbackFn, thisArg?) -> Array
  - forEach(callbackFn, thisArg?) -> undefined
- Copy behavior is shallow; object references are copied, not deep-cloned.

Reference Details

API specifications and exact behavior
- Iterator methods: keys() -> Iterator of indexes; values() -> Iterator of values (treat empty slots as undefined); entries() -> Iterator of [index,value].
- Empty-slot behavior summary: forEach/Map/filter skip empty slots; keys/entries/values iterate across empty slots treating them as undefined.

Best practices and implementation examples
- Use [...arr] or arr.slice() to create a shallow copy before mutating to preserve original array when required.
- Use Array.from when converting array-like or iterable sources to real arrays.

